definition: The act of abandoning, or the state of being abandoned; total desertion; relinquishment.

1. To beat down; to overthrow. 2. To bring down or reduce from a higher to a lower state, number, or degree; to lessen; to diminish; to contract; to moderate; to cut short; as, to abate a demand; to abate pride, zeal, hope. 3. To deduct; to omit; as, to abate something from a price. Nine thousand parishes, abating the odd hundreds. Fuller.
1. A man of mettle or spirit; a gay; fashionable man; a young blood. 2. One fond of paying attention to ladies. 3. One who wooes; a lover; a suitor; in a bad sense, a seducer.
1. The quality or state of being incredible; incredibleness. 2. That which is incredible.

1. The act of incrusting, or the state of being incrusted. 2. A crust or hard coating of anything upon or within a body, as a deposit of lime, sediment, etc., from water on the inner surface of a steam boiler.
1. A sitting on eggs for the purpose of hatching young; a brooding on, or keeping warm, (eggs) to develop the life within, by any process.
A small body moving through space, or revolving about the sun, which on entering the earth's atmosphere would be deflagrated and appear as a meteor.
Not capable of being painted or described.
A membrane extending between the toes of a bird, and uniting them more or less closely together.
A date put to a bill of exchange or other paper, later than that when it was actually made.
The powdered leaves of the baobab tree, used by the Africans to mix in their soup, as the southern negroes use powdered sassafras.
A feast at the time of shearing lambs.
To subject to abusive ridicule expressed in writing; to make the subject of a lampoon.
To execise or have the power of memory; as, some remember better than others.
To migrate again; to go back; to return.
Inclined to remit punishment; lenient; clement.
A smart, ready, and witty reply.
Found; gained by finding.
To exceed in odor.
To surpass in speed of riding; to ride beyond or faster than.
The place or opening by which anything is let out; a passage out; an exit; a vent.
A small house or building at a little distance from the main house; an outbuilding.
To face or look (one) out of countenance; to resist or bear down by bold looks or effrontery; to brave.

One of the small bones or particles of calcareous or other hard substance in the internal ear of vertebrates, and in the auditory organs of many invertebrates; an ear stone. Collectively, the otoliths are called ear sand and otoconite.
The cavity in the skull in which the parts of the internal ear are lodged.
A winding, crooked, or involved course; as, the meanders of the veins and arteries.
An old game at cards.
To throw onto confusion or disorder; to render maudlin.
An order of marsipobranchs including the lampreys. The suckerlike moth contains numerous teeth; the nasal opening is in the middle of the head above, but it does not connect with the mouth.
